  "prompt": "What would be the quadratic equation for the roots 2+\u221a2 and 2-\u221a2?",
  "response": "To find the quadratic equation given the roots \\(2 + \\sqrt{2}\\) and \\(2 - \\sqrt{2}\\), we can use the fact that if \\(r_1\\) and \\(r_2\\) are the roots of a quadratic equation, then the equation can be written in the form:\n\n\\[ (x - r_1)(x - r_2) = 0 \\]\n\nGiven the roots \\(r_1 = 2 + \\sqrt{2}\\) and \\(r_2 = 2 - \\sqrt{2}\\), we substitute these values into the equation:\n\n\\[ (x - (2 + \\sqrt{2}))(x - (2 - \\sqrt{2})) = 0 \\]\n\nWe can simplify this by recognizing it as a difference of squares:\n\n\\[ (x - 2 - \\sqrt{2})(x - 2 + \\sqrt{2}) = 0 \\]\n\nLet \\(x - 2 = y\\), then the equation becomes:\n\n\\[ (y - \\sqrt{2})(y + \\sqrt{2}) = 0 \\]\n\nNow, using the difference of squares formula \\(a^2 - b^2 = (a - b)(a + b)\\):\n\n\\[ y^2 - (\\sqrt{2})^2 = 0 \\]\n\n\\[ y^2 - 2 = 0 \\]\n\nSubstitute back \\(y = x - 2\\):\n\n\\[ (x - 2)^2 - 2 = 0 \\]\n\nExpand and simplify:\n\n\\[ x^2 - 4x + 4 - 2 = 0 \\]\n\n\\[ x^2 - 4x + 2 = 0 \\]\n\nThus, the quadratic equation with roots \\(2 + \\sqrt{2}\\) and \\(2 - \\sqrt{2}\\) is:\n\n\\[ x^2 - 4x + 2 = 0 \\]",
